\section{What perimeter means}{

Perimeter is the total length of \strong{shared cell edges} between a patch cell
and any cell that is not part of that patch, plus any edges on the grid
border. Diagonal contact contributes \strong{nothing}: two cells touching only at
a corner share no physical boundary. This holds regardless of whether the
patch was labelled with 4- or 8-connectivity --- connectivity decides what is
one patch, not where its boundary runs.

Non-square cells are handled correctly. An edge shared with a left/right
neighbour runs north--south and is \code{yres} long; an edge shared with an
up/down neighbour runs east--west and is \code{xres} long. The counts of each are
reported separately (\code{edge_ns_cells}, \code{edge_ew_cells}) as exact integers.
}

\section{Habitat edge versus domain edge}{

\code{perimeter = edge_valid + edge_domain}, and the split matters:
\itemize{
\item \code{edge_valid} --- boundary against an in-domain, known cell. The patch
genuinely stops here. This is real habitat edge.
\item \code{edge_domain} --- boundary against a masked-out cell, a missing cell, or the
grid border. The patch may well continue; we cannot see it.
}

\code{touches_domain_edge} flags patches with any \code{edge_domain}. \strong{Their \code{cells},
\verb{area_*} and \code{perimeter} are lower bounds}, and they are usually the patches
you want to exclude from a size distribution.
}

\section{Geographic rasters}{

Lon/lat grids are supported exactly, not approximated as planar. Cell area
and east--west extent vary with latitude but are constant within a raster
row, so per-row geodesic geometry is used to weight the accumulation: \code{area_m2}
comes from \code{\link[terra:cellSize]{terra::cellSize()}} and edge lengths from geodesic per-row
distances. Metres are the unit for lon/lat regardless of \code{units}.
}

